A Review of Cyber Security Management Standards Applied in
Higher Education Institutions

Abstract The penetration of information systems, computer networks, and websites has become a serious
concern for many organizations in recent years. Despite the computer security protection tools of organizations,
computer and system penetration rate, using different means, kept rising. Information systems face a variety
of risks such as information theft and information destroying through natural disasters and malware attacks.
These threats are the most harmful to data related to users and information systems. These attacks can be
unintentional, such as human error and natural disasters. Given the importance of information security and
the cyber security for academic institutions, it has become indispensable necessity to develop information
security standards, especially, in light of the continuous development in information technology, methods of
penetrating data and information. Therefore, so many international organizations have developed standards
and frameworks to standardize the control information security. These organizations mainly include
International Organization for Standardization (ISO) and National Institute of Standards and Technology
(NIST). The aim of this study is to describe and analyze the ISO and NIST CSF standards for the management
of the Cyber Security systems, in order to identify the policies and guidelines included in the standards that
can serve information security in Higher Education Institutions (HEIs).
Keywords Cyber Security, Information Security, Data Security, ISO/IEC 27001, NISF-CSF, Moroccan
Higher Education Institutions.
I. INTRODUCTION
The secure connection to virtual systems is an important
element in a learning environment as education is
increasingly shifting towards digital learning through online
information sharing, online education, and online assessment.
For the public to trust digital environment, organizations
should provide concrete tools to protect their systems and user
data. Therefore, the use of international standards such as ISO
27001/2/3/5/32, and Cybersecurity frameworks, such as,
NIST Cybersecurity framework NIST-CSF, is the first step
towards providing a trustworthy and secure digital
environment for e-learning.
Given the value of the data they hold, academic institutions
such as universities have become a target for attacks that can
come from both outside and inside the institution. As a result,
efforts are made to protect the IT infrastructure on campuses.
Hence, a significant increase in budgets which are allocated
to cybersecurity.
The risk of a cyberattacks increases due to the openness that
colleges and universities spread. Such spirit challenges these
universities to develop and implement methods to protect
system and user vital data.
Unlike other organizations, universities must manage the
high diversity of targets of these attacks, i.e. students, who
may be particularly vulnerable to phishing attacks, especially
junior students. Since email is the main communication mean
in universities, business office, and housing, etc., it can be
easy to get caught up in a malicious message, especially if it
is well imitated and sent at the right time. Hence, staff
awareness to certain basic security threats and rules is
essential. This step can be accompanied by training
workshops and the implementation of tools to assist in the
implementation of good practices. This paper investigates
also cybersecurity awareness in higher education and
academic institutions to assess the state and risks of
cybersecurity and focus on best practices that can improve
cybersecurity awareness. Finally, we aim, through this
research paper, to describe and analyze the ISO/IEC 27001
and NIST-CSF standards for the management of the
Cybersecurity systems, to identify the policies and guidelines
included in the standards.
The rest of this paper is organized as follows:
The first section reviews the most important
differences between information security and
Cybersecurity.
The second section presents the most important
international standards and laws for information
security and Cybersecurity.
The third section discovers and analyses Cyber Risks
in Higher Education Institutions.
The fourth section discusses elements, policies and
guidelines between ISO/IEC 27001 for information
security and NIST Cybersecurity Framework NIST-
CSF
II. DEMYSTIFYING INFORMATION SECURITY AND
CYBERSECURITY
According to Klimburg et .al [6] Cyber security has
become a matter of world interest and importance. Already
quite 50 nations have formally revealed security strategy
document outlining their official stance on computer
networks, cybercrime, and/or cybersecurity.
Cybersecurity is an all-inclusive term that means
measures taken to protect a computer or computer system (as
on the Internet) against unauthorized access or attack [7].
However, the International Telecommunications Union (ITU)
states these measures and defines Cybersecurity as follows:
Cybersecurity is the collection of tools, policies, security
concepts, security safeguards, guidelines, risk management
approaches, actions, training, best practices, assurance and
technologies that can be used to protect the cyber environment
and organization and users assets. Organization and users
assets include connected computing devices, personnel,
infrastructure, applications, services, telecommunications
systems, and the totality of transmitted and/or stored
information in the cyber environment [8].
Cybersecurity strives to make sure the achievement and
maintenance of the safety properties of the organization and
users assets against relevant security risks within cyberspace.
The general security objectives comprise the following:
Integrity, Availability and Confidentiality, which can also
include authenticity and nonrepudiation [8]. As a matter of
fact, these definitions are very similar to that of information
security, such point of view is supported by the international
standard ISO/IEC 27032:2012(E) [15].
The international standard, ISO/IEC 27002 (2013), defines
information security as the preservation of the confidentiality,
integrity and availability of information [14]. In the context
this standard, information can take on many forms. It can be
printed or written on paper, stored electronically, transmitted
by post or electronic means, shown on films, conveyed in
conversation, etc [14].
According to [14], Information Security aims to:
Protect computer systems from illegal access or
tampering with information During storage,
processing, or transmission.
Protect against disruption of service of legitimate
users.
Detect and repel threats in documents.
Encompasses all the protection of information that
may exist or not in a computer.
Strengthen information and data security
Provide encryption, storage, physical insurance,
security information management and Risks.
Whitman et .al [17] define information security as the
protection of information and its critical elements, including
the systems and hardware that use, store, and transmit that
information. Hence, ensuring the confidentiality, integrity
and availability of information, also known in information
security as the CIA triangle, has traditionally been the
industry standard. Moreover, they state that The security of
these three characteristics of information is as important today
as it has always been, but the CIA triangle model no longer
adequately addresses the constantly changing environment of
the computer industry.
As a conclusion, many current publications dealing with
Cybersecurity use this term interchangeably with the term
information security even if they are not the same.
Cyberspace is the fifth new field of modern wars after land,
sea, air and real space. It represents all the computer networks
that exist around the world, including electronic devices
connected through optical fiber and wireless networks.
Cyberspace is not only the Internet but many other connected
networks [16].
As stated in [16,17], the goal of Cybersecurity is to:
Ensure the continuity of the work of information
systems.
Enhance the protection, confidentiality and privacy
of personal data.
Take all necessary measures to protect citizens and
consumers alike from potential risks in various areas
of Internet use.
Protect operating systems from any attempts to
inadvertently access improper targets.
Establish a national cybersecurity industry.
Protect the vital interests and national security and
its sensitive infrastructure
Strengthen the protection of operational technology
systems and their hardware and software, services
and data.
Take into account the growing vital importance of its
specialization.
Enhance network protection.
Venn diagram can be very helpful to understand the
differences between Cyber Security and Information
Security:
In the diagram above, we see that the left side of the Venn
diagram represents the information security (which consist of
information both digital and analog), while right side
represents the Cybersecurity (things which are vulnerable
through, it includes information, both physical and digital),
So, people have different point of view about these terms,
but generally use them alternatively.
The figure below, shows the comparison of google search
volume of terms Cyber security, Cybersecurity, and
Information security for the last 9 years.
We can see that the search volume for the term
Information Security was higher than the term
cybersecurity historically, but since 2014 Cybersecurity has
had a higher search volume than Information Security.
III. CYBER SECURITY AWARENESS IN ACADEMIA
A. Cyber Risks in Academic Institutions
Following the directives and directions of the new reforms,
which promote the integration of information and
communication technologies ICT in academia such as E-
learning plate-forms, E-mail, WIFI, Web applications, Radio,
etc. Therefore, decision-makers, can have access to rich data
through these tools in order to develop strong learning
strategies.
The adoption of these ICTs in learning processes, have put
academia at high risk of devastating attacks. Colleges and
universities report staggering rates of cyberattacks, with
millions of piracies attempts in information systems every
week [1]. Higher education institutions (HEIs) are also at risk
of losing valuable intellectual property such as patents
granted to staff faculty and students. Because of the frequency
of cyber-attacks on institutions of higher education, the need
to increase cyber awareness has never been greater [1,2,3].
Almost no government body is more vulnerable than public
higher education institutions. This is due to the use of diverse
computer technology by a wide public of students without any
concern or realistic resources to manage security risks. These
risks have been clearly revealed in recent years with the
increase in attacks on public institutions and taking ever-
changing forms. These attacks targeted student information
and professor resources which were stolen or compromised
[4,40,41,42].
According to Ranger et .al [18] many of the Cybersecurity
threats in universities are generating from students who are
eager to learn and identify themselves during their young age.
In recent statistics, there is a large number of students who
venture into programming, for about 18.5 million individuals,
with 11 million professional software engineers and 7.5
million amateurs. While hacking in itself can be a productive
activity for young people, some student turn their attention to
cracking university systems and commit petty crimes, such as
changing their grades and degrees in the online public
university system. Although college students who commit
such crimes are nothing new, younger students have also
managed to bypass university firewalls and tamper with their
grades [20].
While HEIs are great at educating the next generation of
leaders, they are not always good at securing their IT
infrastructure. In fact, more than three-quarters of educational
institutions surveyed by Netwrix [19] said they were not
prepared for IT risks. The survey found that the most
neglected areas of security are BYOD, unstructured data and
employees activity. Almost half of the respondents reported
security incidents as a result of human behavior, while more
than a third had experienced security incidents caused by
malware. Thirty-five per cent of respondents said they were
dealing with stringent data protection requirements [19].
In this environment of growing cyberthreats, where is the
reason why universities are not prepared to meet them?
1. The lack of IT Security Staff:
Most Education Institutions do not have a dedicated IT
security professional. This lack is essentially due to the
absence of an organization chart defining the job in question,
and also the limited budget heading dedicated to training
courses and certifications - which requires the involvement of
professionals in the cybersecurity field - which might be very
expensive.
2. The lack of a Data Center infrastructure
Not all HEIs have dedicated and well-structured data centers.
These new factors have produced a dynamic application
environment based on an essentially static physical
environment, this has increased the complexity of data centers
and introduced new challenges to the management of physical
infrastructure. The biggest problem faced by universities in
many countries, is the highly decentralized nature of their
infrastructure. University systems consist of several schools,
colleges, departments and offices, meaning that responsibility
for university security is usually decentralized. Each college
or department has its own policies, procedures, and security
tools. This approach can make HEIs easy and profitable
targets for cyber-attacks [43,44,45].
B. Cybersecurity Approach in HEIs
Universities must develop and implement a global and
integrated cybersecurity strategy in order to ensure a balance
between the final objective of guaranteeing the security of
their data, and the costs spent in setting up new technological
infrastructures and training the administrative staff dedicated
to their operation and development. The different components
of this strategy must act in a complementary and synchronous
way, in order to preserve the information system as a whole -
System Accounts, Data, and users privacy.
Implementing an integrated approach for cyber security in
HEIs means overcoming decentralization and engaging
everyone at the university on the same page, starting with
support from the management for a safer IT program. They
must understand the potential security implications of a
decentralized approach [24,25,45]. Once the strategy is
implemented, they should assess the security environment
using one of the most famous framework/standards for
Cybersecurity management as the NIST-CSF or ISO/IEC
27001 as a baseline. This not only enables them to identify
security vulnerabilities, but also provides a roadmap to
address them [26].
In the next step, cybersecurity department should develop
a risk management plan, which includes making changes
throughout the system and breaking down traditional means.
Therefore, we propose five important key security areas to
focus on when implementing an approach for cyber security
Management and Awareness in HEIs.

IV. INTERNATIONAL STANDARDS AND LAWS FOR
INFORMATION SECURITY AND CYBERSECURITY
A. International Organization for Standardization ISO
One of the most important standards issued by ISO is the
set of Information Security Standards, which is called
Information Security Management System (ISO/IEC
27000). This standard consists of many sub-standards that are
the most important for this study [27]:
ISO/IEC 27001: Specifies an Information Security
Management System (ISMS), a suite of activities
concerning the management of information risks
(called information security risks in the standard).
ISO/IEC 27002: Rules of Practice for Information
Security Management Systems ISMS.
ISO/IEC 27003: Information Security Management
Implementation Manual.
ISO/IEC 27004: Measuring the effectiveness of
information security management systems.
ISO/IEC 27005: Information Security Risk
Management.
ISO/IEC 27006: A guide to the process of
maintaining an information security management
system
ISO/IEC 27032: Information technology
Security techniques Guidelines for cybersecurity
ISO/IEC 27001
ISO/IEC 27001 formally defines the Information Security
Management System (ISMS) as a set of activities related to
information risk management (called information security
risk in the standard) [13,14,15]. ISMS is a comprehensive
management framework within which an organization
identifies, analyzes, and manages its information risks.
ISMS ensures that security arrangements are adjusted to
keep pace with changes in security threats, vulnerabilities and
business impacts.
The standard covers all types of organizations (such as
businesses, government and non-profit organizations), all
sizes (from small businesses to large multinationals) and all
industries or markets (such as retail, banking, defense,
healthcare, education and government) [13].
ISO/IEC 27001 does not formally enforce specific
information security controls because the required controls
vary significantly across a wide range of organizations that
adopt the standard. Information security controls from
ISO/IEC 27002 are referenced in Annex A to ISO/IEC
27001,
Organizations that adopt ISO/IEC 27001 have the freedom
to choose which information security controls applicable to
their information risks, depending on those listed and may
complement them with other optional options (sometimes
known as extended control groups). As with ISO/IEC 27002,
the key to selecting applicable controls is to conduct a
comprehensive risk assessment, which is a vital part of ISMS
[39,40].
Furthermore, management may choose to avoid, share or
accept information risks rather than mitigate through controls
the risk management decision in the risk management
process.
History [13].
ISO/IEC 27001 is derived from BS 7799 Part 2,
which was first published as such by the British
Standards Institute in 1999.
BS 7799 Part 2 was revised in 2002, and explicitly
incorporated the Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle.
BS 7799 Part 2 was adopted as an ISO/IEC 27001
in 2005 with various changes to reflect its new
trustees.
The first edition of 2005 was widely revised and
published in 2013, making it compatible with other
ISO management systems standards and dropping a
clear reference to the PDCA.
Structure of ISO/IEC 27001
Table below illustrate the sections of ISO/IEC 27001:2013
[13,14]
Annex A contains a set of 35 control objectives and 114
general security controls, grouped in 14 sections, that provide
guidance on how to deal with risks that are identified as
unacceptable.
The list of ISO/IEC 27002 is a standard which means that
accredited organizations are expected to guarantee the
standard requirements. However, one can deviate from these
guidance in order to address their information risks [14].
ISO/IEC 27032
Officially, ISO/IEC 27032 addresses cybersecurity or
cyber space security, as maintaining the confidentiality,
integrity and availability of information in cyberspace.
Cyberspace (complete with a specific essay and Capital) is
defined as the complex environment resulting from the
interaction of people, programs and services on the Internet
through devices, networks, which do not exist in any physical
form [15].
Purpose of ISO/IEC 27032 [13].
Despite the title, the standard is actually about Internet
security. The first two lines give the game away:
"This document focuses on addressing Internet
security issues and provides technical guidance to
address common Internet security risks ...".
The standard does not directly address cyber
security (eg cyber bullying), cyber-crime, Internet
safety, Internet-related crime, information
infrastructure protection, or cyber warfare.
Structure and content [13].
The main sections are:
5. Overview
6. Assets in the Cyberspace
7. Threats against the security of the Cyberspace
8. Roles of stakeholders in Cybersecurity
9. Guidelines for stakeholders
10. Cybersecurity controls
11. Framework of information sharing and coordination
Annex A. Cybersecurity readiness
Annex B. Additional resources
Annex C. Examples of related documents
History [13].
The standard was first published in 2012; yet now it is
being revised with a new work title: Cyber security - Internet
Security Guidelines. The first draft of the review has been
published in 2021. However, since 2012, Cybersecurity has
become a buzzword which people dont know what it actually
means.
B. National Institute of Standards and Technology
Cybersecurity Framework NIST-CSF
Cybersecurity Framework (CSF) is the common name of
the document Framework for Improving Critical
Infrastructure Cybersecurity, published by the National
Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) on February
12, 2014 [21,22,23].
The cybersecurity framework was created after the 2013
US presidential decree to improve cybersecurity, initially
aimed at US companies with critical infrastructures.
However, it is also applicable to any company that faces
security risks [21,22,23].
The CSF follows the President's Executive Order
Improving Cyber Security for Critical Infrastructure issued
in 2013, initially intended for US companies that are part of
critical infrastructure (such as communications, information
technology, defense industry base, etc.). However, they are
suitable for use by any organization facing cyber security
risks, although they are voluntary. The framework is divided
into three parts as illustrated in the figure below [21]:
The NIST-CSF framework is better structured when it is
used for planning and implementation.
As we see in the figure 4, the framework is divided into 5
functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond and Recover, 22
categories (asset management, risk management, etc., it is
similar to Annex A of ISO/IEC 27001) and 98 subcategories
(almost like ISO/IEC 27001 controls). Each subcategory
contains multiple references to other frameworks and
standards such as: ISO/IEC 27001, COBIT, NIST SP 800-53,
ISA 62443. This way of presenting things makes looking for
requirements to implement and where to find them much
easier.
The framework also indicates the levels of implementation
(partial, Risk informed, repeatable, adaptive) that represent
the maturity level of implementation of the latter's controls.
With this, the company can easily decide how far they want
to go with the application of cyber security [22].
V. ANALYSIS
In order to choose between two separate programs
successfully, it is important to understand their differences
and similarities. As a result, we can know how to integrate or
choose between these two programs. So, lets first start with
the common points between ISO/IEC 27001 and NIST-CSF.
A. ISO/IEC 27001 and NIST-CSF similarities
Methodology-based implementation: ISO/IEC 27001
and NIST-CSF provide methodologies for how to
implement cyber security and information security in the
organization. Although their steps are not 100% aligned,
simple adjustments can narrow gaps easily.
Figure 5 illustrate similarities between ISO/IEC 27001 and
NIST-CSF
From the table below, we can see that the NIST-CSF is more
focused and detailed on the operating phase of planning. This
happens because the NIST-CSF assumes that any
organization already has management practices in place, and
that the cyber security framework must be integrated with
them.
Security implementation based on risk management
and recommendations: In both approaches, security
controls and safeguards are applied only if the risks are
unacceptable and provide references for monitoring
development [28].
Table below present similarities between ISO/IEC 27001
Annex A control sections and NIST-CSF control categories
[28].
Cross-Industry Applicability: Although NIST-CSF
was created for use by US organizations as part of a "vital
social infrastructure", it can be applied to any type of
organization, as well as ISO/IEC 27001.
Technological neutrality: NIST-CSF and ISO/IEC
27001 rely on general concepts of security, giving
organizations the freedom to adopt the most
environmentally friendly technologies.
Focus on adding value to business: NIST-CSF and
ISO/IEC 27001, as their ultimate goal, provide business
benefits through risk management, taking into account
legal and regulatory requirements, as well as the
requirements of all parties involved.
B. ISO/IEC 27001 and NIST-CSF differences
In the last section we have seen which points these two
approaches have in common, now, well take a look at their
differences [28,29]:
The NIST-CSF provides better support for the
implementation of controls and safeguards: In
addition to ISO/IEC 27001, NIST-CSF works alongside
with other well-known frameworks and best practices,
such as COBIT (Control Objectives for Information and
Related Technologies), ISA 62443 (Security for
Industrial Automation and Control Systems), NIST SP
800-53 (Security and Privacy Controls for Federal
Information Systems and Organizations) and CCS CSC
(Council on Cyber Security Top 20 Critical Security
Controls), making NIST-CSF more convenient for
integration than ISO/IEC 27001Cybersecurity
Framework provides a basis for self-assessment and
definition of objectives [30,31,32,33,34,35,36,37,38].
ISO/IEC 27001 is certifiable: One of the biggest
advantages of the ISO/IEC 27001 is that organizations
can become certified, which can be useful if they want to
prove to their customers, partners and government
agencies the mastery of the security of their information
system.
ISO/IEC 27001 is internationally recognized: No
matter how good the NIST-CSF is, if any organization
outside the United States wants to demonstrate its ability
to protect its customers, partners and other stakeholders
from the dangers of the Internet, ISO/IEC 27001 will be
a much better option than NIST-CSF.
ISO/IEC 27001 goes beyond IT: IT environments are
just one aspect to consider when we want to protect
information. Paper information, as well as information
flowing through conversations and meetings, should also
be protected, and ISO/IEC 27001 is better prepared to
manage these situations.
Unlike the NIST framework, ISO/IEC 27001 clearly
defines the documents and records to be provided and
which baseline should be implemented.
To summarize, while the NIST-CSF framework focuses
solely on how to plan and implement cybersecurity, ISO/IEC
27001 takes a much broader approach. Its PDCA-based
methodology (Plan, Do, Check, Act) not only implements
but also maintains the entire system in the event of an audit.
C. Which one to choose?
The best thing is to combine ISO/IEC 27001 and NIST-
CSF together. The NIST-CSF is better when it comes to
structuring the security domains to implement while the
ISO/IEC 27001 is better at controlling and designing a long-
term information security management system.
The best result can be achieved if the design of cyber
security is in accordance with ISO 27001 (chapters 4 to 10)
and the scoping of the security and risk management
perimeters is done according to NIST-CSF guidelines.
VI. INTEGRATION OF ISO/IEC 27001 AND NIST-CSF IN HEIS
By reviewing the similarities and differences between
NIST-CSF and ISO/IEC 27001, we can note that their
combination can bring more advantages than complications to
deploy them in HEIs.
We have three scenarios to consider:
1. A Higher Education Institute HEI has already
implemented ISO/IEC 27001 and wishes to adopt
NIST-CSF.
2. A HEI has already implemented NIST-CSF, and
wants to adopt ISO/IEC 27001.
3. The HEI does not have any approach to information
security or cyber security, looking for solutions.
The NIST-CSF is best suited to determining the security
profiles to be achieved, and the structure of security controls
and safeguards to be implemented, particularly those related
to cyber environments. ISO/IEC 27001 is best suited to
integrate all elements into a coherent system that conforms to
the overall context of the organization's management and
production processes. However, in each scenario, the best
results can be achieved as follows:
A. A Higher Education Institute HEI has already
implemented ISO/IEC 27001 and wishes to adopt NIST-
CSF.
For this scenario, since all elements of the management
system are already in place, the organization must consider:
Review the risk management process, to include the
concepts of the Current Profile and Target Profile.
Use the Statement of Applicability and Framework
Core to create a Current Profile.
Conduct an internal audit of the risk management
process and its controls, taking into account the
NIST-CSF Framework core and framework
implementation layers. In this way, the organization
will have an overview of the compatibility of its
current controls.
Identify the Target Profile, taking into account the
Current Profile, work objectives, security, and
internal audit results.
Prepare action plans to achieve the proposed target
goal.
B. A HEI has already implemented NIST-CSF, and wants to
adopt ISO/IEC 27001.
For this scenario, since most elements of the management
system may not exist officially, the organization must first
consider reviewing the NIST-CSF implemented controls,
taking into account the ISO/IEC 27001 clauses. The following
table can help us focus on the most relevant NIST-CSF
categories:
Table 4: ISO/IEC 27001 and relevant NIST-CSF categories
C. The HEI does not have any approach to information
security or cyber security, looking for solutions.
This situation is easier to deal with because we are having
a clean start. The recommendation for this approach is to
design all information security and cyber security in
accordance with ISO/IEC 27001 (clauses 4, 5, 7, 9 and 10),
and to use the NIST-CSF when it comes to risk management
and its application to the specific cyber security controls and
safeguards.

VII. CONCLUSIONS
Nowadays, the management of cybersecurity has become a
paramount necessity as the number of attacks on personal
information is increasing dramatically, and every second
personal identities are being stolen. In the midst of this
epidemiological storm giving rise to a huge wave of service's
digitalization, most HEIs around the globe have resorted to
adopting strategic choices in order to guarantee the
Cybersecurity of data relating to teachers, students and
administrative staff.
In this work we have surveyed and analyzed the standards
and frameworks for managing information security and
cybersecurity. It turned out that, although ISO/IEC 27001
provides globally recognized practices, this does not mean
that it is the ultimate information security solution. To be
effective, the implementation of security must take a holistic
view, so the more we need to adapt our controls, the more
likely we are to develop strong defenses and improve our
performance. The NIST-CSF is a valuable resource to help
design IT-related controls according to ISO/IEC 27001. By
combining these two approaches, an SEA can achieve more
tangible and cost-effective results in implementing, managing
and operating security controls, as well as improving security
levels and user confidence.
Therefore, about all HEIs have a critical reliance on
information and cyber security environments, so, they should
consider integrating ISO/IEC 27001 and NIST-CSF together,
to develop compatible security practices and stronger online
security, The next step of this work is to propose a framework
that combine between the two studied models for Cyber
security Management dedicated for HEIs and universities.
